You should have two adjustments on your garage door opener that adjust the upward and downward travel of the door.";i:9;s:29:"Garage door jerks on opening.";i:10;s:99:"I have tried limit and force adjustments and checked door movement in tracks not sticking to floor.";i:11;s:49:"Watch the opener carefully as it closes the door.";i:12;s:103:"You will see it bend a little as it stores the energy it took to force the door on to the garage floor.";i:13;s:76:"When you open the door some of that energy returns in the form of a rebound.";i:14;s:25:"That is the jerk you see.";i:15;s:22:"Here is an Experiment.";i:16;s:183:"If there is a little gap at the bottom of your garage door on one side or your garage door has been jerking back and forth its probably because theres uneven tension from the springs.";i:17;s:63:"Who knew you and your garage door could have so much in common.";i:18;s:23:"There are two types of.";i:19;s:138:"If your garage door shakes when opening or closing or sounds like it is going to fall off the track the problem is most often the pulleys.";i:20;s:31:"There are two types of pulleys.";i:21;s:40:"Press Fit Pulleys and Cast Iron Pulleys.";i:22;s:119:"Most companies use a press fit pulley which is made up of two separate pieces attached by ball bearings onto the inner.";i:23;s:77:"There are several reasons why your garage door jerks when closing or opening.";i:24;s:83:"Common causes are a bent track bad rollers or problems with the garage door opener.";i:25;s:129:"You cant afford to ignore these issues as they will strain your opener and if ignored can burn out the motor on your garage door.";i:26;s:80:"If your garage door is jerking it could be a problem with the garage door track.";i:27;s:47:"It might be damaged dirty or have debris in it.";i:28;s:82:"In addition the track needs to be aligned correctly for the door to work properly.";i:29;s:72:"When the rollers hit debris in the track it will cause the door to jerk.";i:30;s:91:"The garage door runs on th